    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-12-20T13:23:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-12-20T13:23:00-05:00" n="245"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d245">
                <head>245. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Mission to the United Nations</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d245fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 303, Agency Files, <gloss
                            target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>, Vol. IX. Secret; Flash; Nodis. Drafted
                        by <persName corresp="#p_HMF1">Herz</persName>; cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_PRF1">Pedersen</persName>, Assistant <persName
                            corresp="#p_DPS1">Secretary De Palma</persName>, and Fry; and approved
                        by the Acting Secretary.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-12-20T18:23:00+00:00">December 20, 1971,
                        1823Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>227889. Subj: <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss>. Ref: A. State 227770, B.
                        <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> 5149.<note n="2" xml:id="d245fn2">See
                            <ref target="#d244">Document 244</ref> and <ref target="#d244fn2"
                            >footnote 2 thereto</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>On further reflection, and in light of ref B, we think it will be safer
                        for us to abstain on <persName corresp="#p_RSS1">Ramphal</persName>, vote no
                        on all candidates other than <persName corresp="#p_JM1">Jakobson</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_WK1">Waldheim</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_ORC1">Ortiz</persName>. There are too many unknowns in the
                        equation and it is possible that unless we veto, <persName corresp="#p_RM1"
                            >Rahnema</persName>, for instance, might just squeak by with nine
                        positive votes. We cannot be certain that others among Five will vote
                        against him.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>After this trial heat, it seems to us that we should accept voting on
                        individual candidates, with results announced after each vote, even if you
                        are unable to obtain order of voting that is most desirable from our point
                        of view. Any candidate receiving nine votes (without veto) would be
                        nominated, but it would be understood that otherwise top candidates could
                        still be reconsidered.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>You might also after the voting approach <persName>Malik</persName> and
                        tell him we are puzzled by continued Soviet veto of <persName
                            corresp="#p_JM1">Jakobson</persName> since it would seem that Finnish
                            <gloss target="#t_SYG1">SYG</gloss> could be attractive to him. You
                        would of course <pb facs="0478" n="441" xml:id="pg_441"/> counter the
                        allegation that Arabs are against him by pointing out that Arabs are far
                        from united and some important Arab countries either favor him or have said
                        they can live with him. Purpose of this approach would be to smoke out
                        Soviets whether they intend to veto <persName corresp="#p_JM1"
                            >Jakobson</persName> indefinitely.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>As for <persName corresp="#p_CCF1">Cuevas Cancino</persName>, while he is
                        Western-oriented and even pro-American (in contrast to <persName
                            corresp="#p_GRA1">Garcia Robles</persName>) we think he would make a
                        weak Secretary General and certainly less acceptable to us from that point
                        of view than <persName corresp="#p_ORC1">Ortiz</persName> or <persName
                            corresp="#p_WK1">Waldheim</persName>, so would not wish to see him
                        encouraged at this point.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Irwin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
